0
00:01:12,700 --> 00:01:14,213
I have many girls.

1
00:01:15,180 --> 00:01:16,932
Come. Come. I show you.

2
00:01:21,260 --> 00:01:22,375
Look.

3
00:02:11,940 --> 00:02:13,009
Nice?

4
00:02:15,060 --> 00:02:16,379
I'll take this one.

5
00:02:31,580 --> 00:02:32,729
Look.

6
00:02:33,740 --> 00:02:35,253
What's wrong with her?

7
00:02:35,940 --> 00:02:37,259
Bound feet.

8
00:02:37,860 --> 00:02:39,691
Very special.

9
00:02:40,940 --> 00:02:41,929
Yes?

10
00:02:42,900 --> 00:02:44,094
I'll take her.

11
00:02:44,740 --> 00:02:45,809
Sale.

12
00:03:15,580 --> 00:03:16,979
I must be out of my mind

13
00:03:17,060 --> 00:03:20,496
to be out here in the middle of nowhere
with these little bitches.

14
00:03:20,820 --> 00:03:22,538
That's right. Eat up.

15
00:03:22,620 --> 00:03:24,815
I need you girls nice and healthy.

16
00:03:30,020 --> 00:03:31,897
Stop staring at me like that.

17
00:03:34,500 --> 00:03:36,650
Maybe what you need is a lesson, huh?

18
00:03:40,340 --> 00:03:42,296
That's what these girls need,

19
00:03:43,140 --> 00:03:44,289
a lesson.

20
00:05:51,860 --> 00:05:53,373
Just hold her there.

21
00:06:17,180 --> 00:06:18,329
I got it.

22
00:06:21,100 --> 00:06:23,216
Bring it in, Billy. Come on, let's go.

23
00:06:33,180 --> 00:06:34,295
Keep it steady.

24
00:06:42,060 --> 00:06:43,379
There you go.

25
00:06:59,260 --> 00:07:01,410
I'm looking for a Tom Harte.

26
00:07:03,340 --> 00:07:04,534
I'm his uncle.

27
00:07:04,700 --> 00:07:06,258
Harte's got a family?

28
00:07:06,820 --> 00:07:08,139
Who would have figured?

29
00:07:12,540 --> 00:07:13,768
Tom, boy.

30
00:07:15,420 --> 00:07:16,773
Young Tom.

31
00:07:19,420 --> 00:07:21,297
Jack, this is my uncle, Print.

32
00:07:22,140 --> 00:07:23,493
Print Ritter.

33
00:07:28,420 --> 00:07:30,138
What brings you out this far?

34
00:07:30,980 --> 00:07:32,652
I thought maybe you'd gone under.

35
00:07:32,740 --> 00:07:33,809
No, sir.

36
00:07:33,900 --> 00:07:35,811
I ain't gone under yet. No, sir.

37
00:07:37,860 --> 00:07:39,293
But your mother did.

38
00:07:40,140 --> 00:07:41,971
She passed away two weeks ago.

39
00:07:43,100 --> 00:07:45,694
Her hired man found her
in the vegetable garden.

40
00:07:49,580 --> 00:07:51,491
Is he taking care of the place now?

41
00:07:52,660 --> 00:07:53,649
Yes, sir.

42
00:07:58,900 --> 00:08:00,936
I need to say something straight out.

43
00:08:02,460 --> 00:08:03,939
She wrote a will.

44
00:08:04,820 --> 00:08:07,254
She left it all to me.
Now, I don't know why she done it,

45
00:08:07,340 --> 00:08:10,138
or what was crossed between you two,
but she done it.

46
00:08:10,220 --> 00:08:12,290
The land, the livestock, everything.

47
00:08:13,260 --> 00:08:15,899
It ain't a fortune, but it's legit.

48
00:08:17,740 --> 00:08:18,889
Is that it?

49
00:08:19,980 --> 00:08:21,095
That's it.

50
00:08:25,260 --> 00:08:27,455
Well, she did write this letter to you

51
00:08:27,900 --> 00:08:29,174
a while back.

52
00:08:30,740 --> 00:08:32,492
Your name, Tom, is on there.

53
00:08:39,140 --> 00:08:42,052
I don't feel good about this at all.
That's why I come out here.

54
00:08:42,980 --> 00:08:44,379
I want to talk.

55
00:08:46,140 --> 00:08:47,175
You see,

56
00:08:48,500 --> 00:08:50,934
your mother made me
the executor to her will.

57
00:08:51,420 --> 00:08:54,253
She left everything to me,
except there was a codicil.

58
00:08:54,740 --> 00:08:56,412
You could buy the old Fairburn place,

59
00:08:56,500 --> 00:08:59,810
you know the two sections that run down
from the Steens to the Malheur,

60
00:09:00,380 --> 00:09:01,859
from her estate,

61
00:09:02,140 --> 00:09:03,573
if you've a mind to.

62
00:09:04,260 --> 00:09:05,659
I can buy it?

63
00:09:05,940 --> 00:09:07,532
Yeah. Market price.

64
00:09:12,020 --> 00:09:13,931
The will's on file over the Burns.

65
00:09:16,700 --> 00:09:18,372
Son of a bitch.

66
00:09:19,940 --> 00:09:21,373
That's mother's milk.

67
00:09:22,340 --> 00:09:23,409
Yeah.

68
00:09:23,660 --> 00:09:25,218
More like hind tit.

69
00:09:26,900 --> 00:09:28,777
You know, son, I don't like this
any more than you do

70
00:09:28,860 --> 00:09:31,693
but I got this idea,
might be good for both of us.

71
00:09:31,780 --> 00:09:34,897
I got this idea to take horses
back to Wyoming.

72
00:09:36,340 --> 00:09:38,410
Listen to this, you're gonna like this.

73
00:09:38,500 --> 00:09:39,853
Listen to this.

74
00:09:39,980 --> 00:09:41,095
<i>"</i>Wanted,

75
00:09:41,180 --> 00:09:43,091
<i>"</i>hot or cold-blooded horses.

76
00:09:43,180 --> 00:09:45,057
<i>"</i>Sound and disease-free.

77
00:09:45,140 --> 00:09:46,619
<i>"</i>Three to eight years of age.

78
00:09:46,700 --> 00:09:49,373
<i>"</i>Purchase price commiserate
with the quality of stock.

79
00:09:49,460 --> 00:09:52,418
<i>"</i>Contact William Moncrieffe,
Sheridan, Wyoming.

80
00:09:53,660 --> 00:09:56,811
<i>"</i>Agent for Her Majesty's War Office,
British Empire.<i>"</i>

81
00:09:57,620 --> 00:09:58,973
What do you say?

82
00:09:59,060 --> 00:10:00,618
Like that idea?

83
00:10:03,660 --> 00:10:06,811
Why don't we take some of your ma's money
and buy a big string of horses?

84
00:10:06,900 --> 00:10:09,698
Might be a handy way
to increase our capital.

85
00:10:10,220 --> 00:10:12,814
And I'm thinking tough,
high-desert mustangs.

86
00:10:12,900 --> 00:10:14,492
They can go unshod

87
00:10:14,580 --> 00:10:17,970
and ought to be fairly broke
by the time we get to Sheridan.

88
00:10:21,740 --> 00:10:22,934
On shares?

89
00:10:24,100 --> 00:10:25,249
I figure

90
00:10:25,860 --> 00:10:29,933
a 25-75 split on profits
after expenses and loan repayment.

91
00:10:30,020 --> 00:10:32,090
- Loan repayment?
- To the bank.

92
00:10:32,340 --> 00:10:34,490
I'd have to put the ranch up as collateral.

93
00:10:34,580 --> 00:10:36,730
Well, what the shit kind of deal is that?

94
00:10:37,220 --> 00:10:40,257
You take the family ranch
to borrow money to buy horses?

95
00:10:40,740 --> 00:10:42,173
Well, that's...

96
00:10:42,260 --> 00:10:43,932
That's one way of looking at it.

97
00:10:44,260 --> 00:10:45,488
What's the other?

98
00:10:45,740 --> 00:10:48,971
Well, you can stay here,
cutting the nuts off another man's cows

99
00:10:49,060 --> 00:10:52,575
for chuck and wages till you're all
stove up and walking around like a crab,

100
00:10:52,660 --> 00:10:56,050
like all the other bachelor cowhands
from here to the Dalles.

101
00:10:56,340 --> 00:10:57,898
No disrespect meant.

102
00:11:02,500 --> 00:11:03,728
Truth is,

103
00:11:04,420 --> 00:11:06,650
you're as loose as ashes in the wind.

104
00:11:15,060 --> 00:11:17,415
How many horses you say we can handle?

105
00:11:17,500 --> 00:11:20,060
Three to five hundred head, give or take.

106
00:11:21,700 --> 00:11:22,735
Well...

107
00:11:23,460 --> 00:11:25,530
Good to see you're still riding old Bob Tate.

108
00:11:25,620 --> 00:11:26,609
You bet.

109
00:11:28,100 --> 00:11:30,011
So, you ready, buckaroo? Let's do it.

110
00:11:36,300 --> 00:11:37,449
Keep going.

111
00:11:47,780 --> 00:11:49,372
The other way.

112
00:11:49,460 --> 00:11:51,496
Go the other way!

113
00:11:52,060 --> 00:11:53,095
Just hold on.

114
00:11:53,180 --> 00:11:55,216
Hold up. Just hold them up to the right.

115
00:12:03,700 --> 00:12:05,019
You heard him.

116
00:12:05,980 --> 00:12:07,379
Move them to the left.

117
00:12:13,020 --> 00:12:14,135
Come on.

118
00:12:15,460 --> 00:12:16,575
Let's do it!

119
00:12:17,620 --> 00:12:19,417
Let's move them out.

120
00:12:20,740 --> 00:12:22,458
Move it! Move it!

121
00:12:25,020 --> 00:12:27,409
Let's move them out. Hold them!

122
00:12:27,780 --> 00:12:29,179
Move them out east.

123
00:12:29,980 --> 00:12:31,015
Let's go.

124
00:12:42,300 --> 00:12:43,653
Get them to a run.

125
00:13:44,620 --> 00:13:46,815
Nothing like a 10-mile romp

126
00:13:47,580 --> 00:13:49,218
to knock the edge off them.

127
00:13:49,300 --> 00:13:53,009
Figured out who's gonna be the caporal
of this mob, Mr Ritter?

128
00:13:53,100 --> 00:13:55,739
I'd say that stout grey,
that flea-bitten mare right there.

129
00:13:55,820 --> 00:13:57,538
You're gonna have your hands full,
Mr Ritter.

130
00:13:57,620 --> 00:14:00,259
You sure you don't want
a couple of us to go along?

131
00:14:00,340 --> 00:14:02,058
No, boys, we can handle it.

132
00:14:02,900 --> 00:14:05,619
That ought to about do it, Vick.
Appreciate the help.

133
00:14:06,780 --> 00:14:09,089
Thank you. See you next spring.

134
00:14:09,180 --> 00:14:10,454
Plan on it.

135
00:14:16,860 --> 00:14:18,009
Come on, boys.

136
00:14:19,580 --> 00:14:20,933
Come on now, boys.

137
00:14:22,300 --> 00:14:24,894
Gonna walk them all the way
to Wyoming, Nephew.

138
00:14:26,060 --> 00:14:27,175
Walk them in the morning.

139
00:14:27,260 --> 00:14:30,252
Graze them at night, all night,
and let them rest.

140
00:14:30,340 --> 00:14:33,810
We don't want to come in
with a bunch of skin and bones. No, sir.

141
00:14:46,780 --> 00:14:49,010
When the Indians first laid eyes on them,

142
00:14:49,100 --> 00:14:50,772
they called them <i>"</i>god dogs.<i>"</i>

143
00:14:51,220 --> 00:14:52,335
<i>"</i>God dogs<i>"</i>?

144
00:14:52,420 --> 00:14:55,696
Yeah, it was the Spanish in them.
Been on the loose for a long time.

145
00:14:56,660 --> 00:15:00,209
Yeah, we ought to think about
coming up here and spending next summer.

146
00:15:01,060 --> 00:15:02,209
Yeah.

147
00:15:02,420 --> 00:15:04,490
Let's get your herd delivered first.

148
00:15:05,460 --> 00:15:08,054
It's a damn sight more yours than it is mine.

149
00:15:08,140 --> 00:15:10,938
Well, I don't feel that way.
Don't think your ma would either.

150
00:15:20,860 --> 00:15:21,975
<i>"</i>Tom.

151
00:15:22,300 --> 00:15:25,815
<i>"</i>As you seem to have had
little interest in the homestead,

152
00:15:25,980 --> 00:15:29,211
<i>"</i>I see no reason to burden you
with its ownership.

153
00:15:29,500 --> 00:15:33,129
<i>"</i>You are free to pursue
your own opportunities.

154
00:15:34,380 --> 00:15:35,574
<i>"</i>Your mother.<i>"</i>

155
00:15:38,620 --> 00:15:39,939
Not very generous.

156
00:15:42,740 --> 00:15:45,652
She never got over
my running off to buckaroo.

157
00:15:47,100 --> 00:15:48,169
Yeah.

158
00:15:49,140 --> 00:15:51,859
Losing your pa made her a hard woman.

159
00:15:54,780 --> 00:15:55,895
Still,

160
00:15:56,420 --> 00:15:58,650
I sent money home after every season.

161
00:16:18,220 --> 00:16:19,414
You know,

162
00:16:19,740 --> 00:16:22,379
sometimes I look up there,
I see those lights,

163
00:16:23,620 --> 00:16:25,178
I think maybe the Old Man

164
00:16:25,660 --> 00:16:28,174
is not too happy with the way
things are down here.

165
00:16:33,020 --> 00:16:34,089
Yeah.

166
00:16:34,180 --> 00:16:35,374
It's funny,

167
00:16:35,980 --> 00:16:38,653
I always got the feeling
it meant he was pleased.

168
00:16:44,700 --> 00:16:45,849
Yeah.

169
00:16:54,940 --> 00:16:56,419
It's a great life

170
00:16:57,780 --> 00:16:59,771
when it ain't raining or snowing.

171
00:17:27,620 --> 00:17:28,655
Come on, boys.

172
00:17:28,740 --> 00:17:29,934
Come on, boys.

173
00:17:34,420 --> 00:17:36,650
Come on, boys. Let's go. Come on.

174
00:17:39,060 --> 00:17:41,130
Nephew, let's go.

175
00:17:44,820 --> 00:17:45,935
Get going.

176
00:17:47,820 --> 00:17:49,492
Wyoming's waiting on us.

177
00:17:54,900 --> 00:17:56,174
Let's do it.

178
00:18:00,180 --> 00:18:02,819
They say Wyoming's hell
on women and horses.

179
00:18:02,900 --> 00:18:06,256
We're going to find out soon enough,
at least one aspect of it.

180
00:18:09,940 --> 00:18:11,373
Where is he taking us?

181
00:18:13,660 --> 00:18:17,539
Our families sold us into service.

182
00:18:21,940 --> 00:18:25,091
He must be very rich to need five servants.

183
00:18:26,580 --> 00:18:29,094
This is not a rich man's cart.

184
00:18:29,780 --> 00:18:31,896
Maybe he plans to kill us.

185
00:18:33,980 --> 00:18:37,290
Why would he buy us just to kill us?

186
00:18:38,940 --> 00:18:40,976
He does not plan to kill us.

187
00:18:41,860 --> 00:18:44,693
But I think we may wish he did.

188
00:18:45,460 --> 00:18:46,779
You girls shut up.

189
00:18:47,580 --> 00:18:49,889
I'm sick of listening to that cackling.

190
00:19:10,620 --> 00:19:13,418
- You feel like going in for supplies?
- Sure.

191
00:19:15,380 --> 00:19:16,972
Go easy on the whisky.

192
00:19:17,060 --> 00:19:20,018
It don't always suit your temperament.
And don't dawdle.

193
00:19:20,300 --> 00:19:23,849
I don't want to be having to worry
about coming to fetch you.

194
00:19:28,220 --> 00:19:29,494
Thank you.

195
00:20:04,700 --> 00:20:05,735
Ma'am.

196
00:20:06,900 --> 00:20:07,969
Howdy.

197
00:20:08,060 --> 00:20:09,493
Hi, can I help you?

198
00:20:09,580 --> 00:20:11,457
I need supplies.

199
00:20:12,500 --> 00:20:13,728
Flour,

200
00:20:13,820 --> 00:20:15,094
bacon,

201
00:20:15,740 --> 00:20:17,332
four sacks of Arbuckles,

202
00:20:17,740 --> 00:20:19,298
some cut tobacco,

203
00:20:20,100 --> 00:20:23,172
and four boxes of therapeutic papers.

204
00:20:30,540 --> 00:20:31,973
Anything else?

205
00:20:34,540 --> 00:20:35,768
You sell whisky?

206
00:20:35,860 --> 00:20:38,055
No, sir. Up the hill at the saloon.

207
00:20:38,300 --> 00:20:39,653
They'll take care of you.

208
00:20:45,540 --> 00:20:46,575
Hi.

209
00:21:03,620 --> 00:21:04,689
Howdy.

210
00:21:04,780 --> 00:21:07,897
Get a shot of whisky
and three bottles to take away?

211
00:21:29,780 --> 00:21:32,453
I thought I told you yesterday,
no panhandling in here.

212
00:21:32,540 --> 00:21:34,417
It's a free country.
I got a right to earn a living.

213
00:21:34,500 --> 00:21:36,013
Not in here. Let's go.

214
00:21:37,580 --> 00:21:39,730
I'd like to hear him play the fiddle.

215
00:21:43,740 --> 00:21:45,332
And who the hell are you?

216
00:21:45,420 --> 00:21:47,729
Just a fellow that enjoys fiddle playing.

217
00:21:47,820 --> 00:21:50,015
I'll kick the both of youse out then. Let's go.

218
00:22:00,740 --> 00:22:01,889
Want a drink?

219
00:22:03,100 --> 00:22:04,499
Don't mind if I do.

220
00:22:05,900 --> 00:22:07,174
It's on him.

221
00:22:07,660 --> 00:22:09,412
- Thank you.
- Welcome.

222
00:22:11,140 --> 00:22:12,289
Much obliged.

223
00:22:34,620 --> 00:22:35,973
I hired a new man.

224
00:22:42,820 --> 00:22:43,809
What for?

225
00:22:46,540 --> 00:22:48,656
I thought you might like some music.

226
00:22:50,660 --> 00:22:52,218
And that's his purpose?

227
00:22:53,260 --> 00:22:57,173
That and to help out with the nighthawking
and pull that pack horse around.

228
00:23:00,980 --> 00:23:03,448
- Does he have a name?
- Yes, sir.

229
00:23:04,060 --> 00:23:05,539
Henry Gilpin.

230
00:23:05,620 --> 00:23:07,053
But you can call me Heck.

231
00:23:08,500 --> 00:23:09,728
All right, Hank.

232
00:23:12,980 --> 00:23:14,732
We'll see what you can do.

233
00:23:14,820 --> 00:23:16,731
Thank you, sir. I appreciate it.

234
00:23:31,620 --> 00:23:32,848
Thank you.

235
00:23:32,940 --> 00:23:34,134
Nature's call.

236
00:23:38,820 --> 00:23:41,254
Man guaranteed me
those therapeutic papers

237
00:23:41,340 --> 00:23:43,012
wouldn't have any splinters in them.

238
00:23:44,140 --> 00:23:45,653
Let you judge that.

239
00:23:45,900 --> 00:23:49,609
Hey, I was thinking we ought to stay off
the main trail as long as possible.

240
00:23:49,700 --> 00:23:51,577
Probably be better forage anyway.

241
00:23:51,660 --> 00:23:54,811
Okay with me
long as the river crossings ain't bad.

242
00:23:55,820 --> 00:23:57,219
How's it going?

243
00:23:57,300 --> 00:23:59,860
Find any wood chips or splinters?

244
00:23:59,940 --> 00:24:03,489
I tell you, it beats corncobs
and sage grass any day.

245
00:24:03,820 --> 00:24:04,935
Yes, sir.

246
00:25:01,100 --> 00:25:02,249
Morning.

247
00:25:03,740 --> 00:25:05,253
Y'all off to church?

248
00:25:07,540 --> 00:25:08,689
No, indeed.

249
00:25:10,580 --> 00:25:12,013
Captain Billy Fender.

250
00:25:13,500 --> 00:25:14,728
Gentlemen,

251
00:25:15,100 --> 00:25:18,615
as you can see, I have purchased,
at a great expense mind you,

252
00:25:19,060 --> 00:25:22,370
five exotic virgins from the Celestial Empire.

253
00:25:22,780 --> 00:25:25,340
I'm headed out to the mining camps,
where those men out there

254
00:25:25,420 --> 00:25:29,015
will pay good money to deflower
one of these little lotus blossoms.

255
00:25:29,420 --> 00:25:32,014
You seem to be travelling
in the same direction.

256
00:25:32,460 --> 00:25:36,373
You gents mind if I tag along?
God only knows I can use the company.

257
00:25:36,860 --> 00:25:38,896
Conversation's been a bit thin.

258
00:26:01,060 --> 00:26:02,288
Pick that up!

259
00:26:09,660 --> 00:26:11,616
Put some more wood on that fire.

260
00:26:16,820 --> 00:26:19,493
Got a couple of extra rabbits,
if you'd care to join us.

261
00:26:19,580 --> 00:26:20,979
Don't mind if I do.

262
00:26:51,660 --> 00:26:53,093
Drink up, gents.

263
00:27:01,740 --> 00:27:02,855
Gentlemen,

